<Base title="Mumbles Restaurant SEO Case Study" description="How a Mumbles restaurant achieved 340% more Google Maps visibility and 50 extra covers per month through local SEO in Swansea. Full case study." schema={schema}>

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-brand mb-4">Mumbles Restaurant — Google Maps SEO Case Study</h1>

  <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg my-4 text-sm text-blue-800">This case study is illustrative and based on composite data from similar local SEO campaigns. It demonstrates typical results achievable for hospitality businesses in the Mumbles area.</div>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg my-6">
    <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1">Quick Answer</p>
    <p class="text-gray-700">A Mumbles restaurant went from invisible in Google Maps to the top 3 local pack within 3 months. The campaign delivered a 340% increase in Maps visibility and approximately 50 additional covers per month through Google Business Profile optimisation, local citations, review strategy, and menu structured data.</p>
  </div>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">This Mumbles restaurant SEO case study illustrates what happens when a hospitality business with excellent food but poor online visibility commits to a structured local SEO campaign. The restaurant sat on Mumbles Road with views across Swansea Bay, served fresh seafood sourced from local boats, and had a loyal base of regulars. Yet it was completely invisible in Google Maps, losing potential customers to competitors who appeared in the local pack for every relevant search. Tourists visiting Mumbles Pier, couples walking along Bracelet Bay, and families exploring the Gower Peninsula were all searching on their phones and finding other restaurants instead.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">This case study documents the 3-month campaign that changed that, covering the specific challenges, the strategy deployed, and the measurable results achieved. It is published to give Swansea hospitality businesses a realistic picture of what local SEO delivers when executed properly. For the companion case study covering organic SEO for trades businesses, see the <a href="/case-studies/morriston-trades-business-organic/" class="text-brand hover:underline">Morriston trades business case study</a>.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4">The Challenge</h2>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The restaurant faced a common problem among Mumbles hospitality businesses: strong offline reputation, weak online presence. Despite being established for several years and maintaining high standards, the business did not appear in the Google Maps local pack for any of its target terms. Searches for "restaurant mumbles," "seafood mumbles," "best restaurant swansea bay," and "restaurant near me" from anywhere along Mumbles Road returned competitors instead.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The root causes were typical for independent restaurants. The Google Business Profile existed but had an incorrect primary category, inconsistent opening hours, no menu information, and only 12 reviews with an average rating of 3.8. The website was a basic template with no structured data, no local content, and load times exceeding 6 seconds on mobile. Local citations across directories were inconsistent, with different phone numbers and addresses listed on TripAdvisor, Facebook, and Yell. The restaurant was effectively telling Google conflicting information about what it was, where it was, and when it was open.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Meanwhile, competitors on Mumbles Road with inferior food but better digital presence dominated the local pack. One competitor had 180 reviews and a fully optimised profile. Another had invested in local content targeting "seafood Gower" and "fine dining Swansea Bay." The restaurant was losing an estimated 50 to 80 potential covers per month to businesses that simply showed up in search results.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4">The Strategy</h2>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The campaign was structured across 3 months with overlapping workstreams targeting all three of Google's local ranking factors: proximity, relevance, and prominence.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Month 1: Foundations</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The first priority was the Google Business Profile. We corrected the primary category to "Seafood Restaurant," added secondary categories for "Restaurant" and "Welsh Restaurant," updated all hours including seasonal variations, uploaded 40 high-quality photos covering food, interior, exterior, and the Swansea Bay view, and wrote a keyword-rich business description mentioning Mumbles, Gower, and Swansea Bay naturally. The menu was added in full with structured categories and pricing.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Simultaneously, we audited and corrected citations across 35 local directories. Every listing was updated to show the same name, address, and phone number. TripAdvisor, Facebook, Yell, Cylex, Thomson Local, and Wales-specific directories like Visit Swansea Bay were all brought into alignment. This consistency signals to Google that the business information is trustworthy.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Month 2: Content and Reviews</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">With foundations in place, month 2 focused on building relevance and prominence. We implemented a review generation strategy: table cards with QR codes linking directly to the Google review page, follow-up emails to diners who booked online, and staff training on when and how to mention reviews naturally. The goal was not to incentivise reviews but to make leaving one as frictionless as possible.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">On the website, we added structured data markup for the restaurant (LocalBusiness schema with menu, opening hours, and geo-coordinates), individual menu items using the Menu and MenuItem schema types, and FAQ schema addressing common queries like parking near Mumbles Pier, dietary options, and booking for large groups. We also published a local content page about dining in Mumbles that naturally referenced Mumbles Road, Bracelet Bay, and the coastal path from Swansea Bay, building topical relevance for the restaurant's location.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Month 3: Refinement and Expansion</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">By month 3, the profile was generating momentum. We expanded Google Business Profile activity with weekly posts featuring seasonal specials and events, responded to every review within 24 hours, and added attributes like outdoor seating, waterfront location, and accepts reservations. We submitted the restaurant to Google's "Popular Times" data feed and ensured the website passed Core Web Vitals on mobile, bringing load time from 6 seconds to under 2 seconds.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">We also targeted expansion terms beyond the immediate Mumbles area: "seafood restaurant swansea," "best fish restaurant gower," and "romantic restaurant swansea bay." These terms brought in customers from the wider Swansea area and tourists planning visits to the Gower Peninsula.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4">The Results</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-4 gap-4 my-8">
    <div class="text-center p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg">
      <span class="text-3xl font-bold text-brand">340%</span>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-1">Maps visibility increase</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-center p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg">
      <span class="text-3xl font-bold text-brand">50</span>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-1">Additional covers/month</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-center p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg">
      <span class="text-3xl font-bold text-brand">Top 3</span>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-1">Local pack position</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-center p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg">
      <span class="text-3xl font-bold text-brand">4.6</span>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-1">Average review rating</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">After 3 months, the restaurant ranked in the top 3 of the Google Maps local pack for its primary target terms: "restaurant mumbles," "seafood mumbles," and "best restaurant swansea bay." Google Maps impressions increased by 340%, translating to approximately 50 additional covers per month based on the restaurant's conversion rate from Maps views to reservations.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Reviews grew from 12 (average 3.8) to 47 (average 4.6) during the campaign period. The profile received "directions" and "call" actions at 4 times the pre-campaign rate. Website traffic from organic search increased by 210%, with the majority coming from mobile devices used by people physically in or near Mumbles.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The restaurant also began appearing in Google's "Popular near Mumbles Pier" and "Restaurants with a view" curated results, which generated additional discovery traffic from tourists who had not searched for the restaurant by name or category.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4">Key Takeaways</h2>

  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    <li>Google Business Profile is the single highest-impact lever for restaurant local SEO. Getting the categories, photos, and hours right delivers more movement than any website change.</li>
    <li>Citation consistency across directories is foundational. Conflicting NAP data actively suppresses local rankings.</li>
    <li>Review velocity matters more than review count. A steady flow of genuine reviews signals ongoing customer satisfaction to Google's algorithm.</li>
    <li>Structured data for menus and local business information gives Google explicit signals that improve rich result eligibility.</li>
    <li>Local content that references genuine landmarks like Mumbles Pier, Bracelet Bay, and the Gower Peninsula builds topical relevance that generic restaurant pages cannot match.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4">Campaign Timeline</h2>

  <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden mb-8">
    <div class="grid grid-cols-3 text-sm">
      <div class="p-4 bg-gray-50 border-b border-r border-gray-200 font-semibold">Month 1</div>
      <div class="p-4 bg-gray-50 border-b border-r border-gray-200 font-semibold">Month 2</div>
      <div class="p-4 bg-gray-50 border-b border-gray-200 font-semibold">Month 3</div>
      <div class="p-4 border-r border-gray-200 text-gray-700">GBP overhaul, citation audit and fixes, photo upload, category correction</div>
      <div class="p-4 border-r border-gray-200 text-gray-700">Review strategy launch, structured data, local content, menu schema</div>
      <div class="p-4 text-gray-700">Weekly GBP posts, Core Web Vitals fix, expansion terms, attribute additions</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-2 mb-8">
    <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
      <summary class="cursor-pointer font-medium text-gray-900 py-2 px-4">How does Google Maps SEO work for restaurants?</summary>
      <div class="px-4 pb-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">Google Maps SEO for restaurants involves optimising your Google Business Profile with accurate categories, hours, and menu information, building consistent local citations across directories, generating genuine customer reviews, and adding structured data like menu markup to your website. Google uses proximity, relevance, and prominence to rank local results, so the strategy addresses all three factors systematically.</div>
    </details>
    <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
      <summary class="cursor-pointer font-medium text-gray-900 py-2 px-4">How long does it take for a restaurant to rank in the Google Maps local pack?</summary>
      <div class="px-4 pb-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">Most restaurants in areas like Mumbles and Swansea Bay can reach the local pack within 8 to 12 weeks with a focused local SEO campaign. The timeline depends on the current state of your Google Business Profile, the number and quality of existing reviews, and how well-optimised your competitors are. Restaurants starting from scratch typically see meaningful movement within the first month and local pack placement by month 3.</div>
    </details>
    <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
      <summary class="cursor-pointer font-medium text-gray-900 py-2 px-4">What is the most important ranking factor for restaurant SEO?</summary>
      <div class="px-4 pb-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">Google Business Profile optimisation is the single most impactful factor for restaurant local SEO. This includes choosing the correct primary and secondary categories, maintaining accurate hours and contact information, regularly posting updates, and responding to reviews. A well-optimised profile with strong reviews consistently outranks restaurants with better websites but neglected profiles.</div>
    </details>
    <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
      <summary class="cursor-pointer font-medium text-gray-900 py-2 px-4">Can SEO replace paid advertising for restaurants in Swansea?</summary>
      <div class="px-4 pb-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">SEO does not replace paid advertising entirely, but it provides a more sustainable and cost-effective channel over time. A restaurant ranking in the Google Maps local pack for terms like "restaurant mumbles" receives clicks without paying per impression or per click. Many Swansea restaurants find that once organic visibility is established, they can reduce ad spend significantly while maintaining or increasing total customer acquisition.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4">Get Similar Results for Your Business</h2>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Whether you run a restaurant in Mumbles, a cafe on Swansea Bay, or a pub in the Gower, the same local SEO principles apply. Start with a <a href="/free-seo-audit-swansea/" class="text-brand hover:underline">free SEO audit</a> to see where your business currently stands and what quick wins are available. Browse our full range of <a href="/services/" class="text-brand hover:underline">SEO services</a> or view more <a href="/case-studies/" class="text-brand hover:underline">case studies</a> to see results across different industries.</p>

